      <bioghist>
         <head>Biographical/Historical Information</head>
         <p>Born in 1936 in Blowing Rock, North Carolina. Went to
         Washington and Lee before spending 3 years in the Air Force in
         Korea. Returned and graduated in 1961 from Richmond
         Professional Institute (now Virginia Commonwealth University).
         Held several positions at the Richmond Times-Dispatch, then
         became part of the counter-culture scene and worked at
         newspapers in New York and San Francisco before settling in
         Seattle. His first book, Another Roadside Attraction, was
         published in 1971 followed by the even more successful Even
         Cowgirls Get the Blues in 1976. He has written seven novels,
         the most recent being Fierce Invalids Home from Hot Climates,
         and many short stories and essays. He continues to write and
         lives in Northwestern Washington.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent>
         <head>Scope and Content Information</head>
         <p>Collection consists of the literary manuscripts for all
         seven of Robbins' novels plus a few of his other smaller
         works. Robbins' writing method for all of his works is to
         handwrite a first draft, have a typist type that up, and then
         use the type written copy for future corrections. The
         handwritten first copies are included in the collection for
         all seven novels. Future drafts of works by Robbins will also
         be added to the collection.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement>
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The collection is organized with the seven novels in
         chronological order.</p>
      </arrangement>
